Code 28: ln command


The ln command in Unix-like operating systems is used to create links between files. It can create two types of links:

Hard Links: These links point directly to the inode of a file, meaning they reference the same physical data on the disk. Changes to one file are reflected in all hard links to that file. Hard links cannot be created for directories or across different file systems.

Symbolic Links (Soft Links): These links are simply pointers to the filename of another file. They can point to directories and can span different file systems. Symbolic links are more flexible than hard links but may become invalid if the target file is deleted or moved.




